</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0C9BBFAEFFBF8B2FED8AFD814CF78E90" pageId="14" pageNumber="193" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="443EEC25FFBF8B2FED8AFD814D5E8E1F" blockId="14.[151,1437,151,752]" box="[199,1389,583,608]" pageId="14" pageNumber="193">
<emphasis id="76F53037FFBF8B2FED8AFD8149758E1F" bold="true" box="[199,326,583,608]" pageId="14" pageNumber="193">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name is explained by the unusually large and round, medal-like reniform stigma.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="443EEC25FFBF8B2FED8AFDAA4CF78E90" blockId="14.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="14" pageNumber="193">
<emphasis id="76F53037FFBF8B2FED8AFDAA49898EFA" bold="true" box="[199,442,620,645]" pageId="14" pageNumber="193">Taxonomic remarks</emphasis>
. A species with particular external characters: the reddish ground colour, the almost complete absence of transverse lines, the white filling and exquisite circular shape of the reniform stigma are all autapomorphies of this taxon. Other morphological features, e.g. the shape of labial palps, the concave costa, the yellow orbicular stigma and the structure of the genitalia assign this taxon to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="838197A6FFBF8B2FE925FD1E4C8F8E8F" box="[1128,1212,728,752]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Naarda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="76F53037FFBF8B2FE925FD1E4C8F8E8F" box="[1128,1212,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="193">Naarda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
